Real Estate
| Square Feet | The 30-Minute Interview 
Douglas C. Yearley Jr.

By VIVIAN MARINOMARCH 24, 2011



Continue reading the main story
Share This Page

Continue reading the main story









Mr. Yearley, 51, is the new chief executive of Toll Brothers Inc., one of the country’s largest builders of luxury homes, with developments in 19 states.Mr. Yearley, formerly the executive vice president, helped spearhead Toll’s expansion into urban markets, including New York City. He took over the daily duties of running the company from Robert I. Toll, a founder, in June.Q  How is the first year as C.E.O.?A I’ve been with the company for 20 years, and I’ve been reporting directly to Bob for 20 years, so the transition was pretty easy.Q  What’s Bob’s role now?A Bob’s executive chairman.I’m running the company day to day. But when it comes to major personnel issues or a major strategic decision, including the review of land opportunities, Bob gets involved.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

Q  Have you instituted any changes?A In terms of strategy, very little has changed. We’re still a luxury builder; we’re still looking to take advantage of the more than $1 billion in cash that we have and buy land now to set up the future. Continue reading the main story







Advertisement

Continue reading the main story





Q  Have you been buying much land with these reserves?A In 2010 we spent $430 million on new land all over the country.We purchased four properties out of the WCI bankruptcy, one of which is Rivington in Danbury, Conn. We bought about 1,000 remaining home sites that are left in Rivington that WCI had started before they went bankrupt. Within a month or two we will start construction on our models.Q  How many projects is Toll Brothers working on?A The company has 200 communities open for sale right now. We own land for another couple hundred that we’re either waiting for a better market or we’re processing approvals or permits. In addition, there are, at any given time, probably 50 to 100 deals that are out there percolating.Q  Let’s talk about projects in the New York area, starting with the Dumbo, Brooklyn, condominium.A We started construction in October. We’ll be starting sales in September, then occupancy the summer of 2012. It will probably average about $800 a square foot, so studios could be $500,000 and penthouses up to $2 million.Q  How about the  Touraine?   A At 65th and Lexington, it’s our first building on the Upper East Side. It’s a boutique building with 23 units — actually 22, since we just combined a couple of units on the top floors. Construction began in the fall. We’re probably going to open for sale in the fall of 2011, and the building will deliver late summer or fall of 2012. The price point there is $2,000 a foot.
Photo






Douglas C. Yearley

Credit
            Marilynn K. Yee/The New York Times        


Q  Have you sold most of the units at 303 East 33rd?A We began sales when Lehman Brothers tanked in 2008, so prices came down. But in the last year they’ve gone back up. We’re about 90 percent sold.Q  How is the New York market faring?A Toll Brothers City Living — which for us is Hoboken, Jersey City, Manhattan and Brooklyn — is our best market in the country.
