The average price now is $1 million; nationwide it’s $560,000.Q  How are sales companywide?A The spring selling season historically begins right after the Super Bowl and runs into the middle of April, so now we’re over a month into the season.It’s been pretty good so far. Deposits are up 9 percent from last year. Deposits can take two to five weeks to convert into an agreement.Q  Has the cancellation rate improved?A It’s back down to historical norms, which is about 7 percent, compared with 30 percent during the recession.Q  But it’s still a buyer’s market.A It’s still a buyer’s market, but it’s strengthening a bit. We’re having pricing power in isolated locations like New York City and Hoboken. Prices aren’t falling in other places; they’re just flat.Q  How will changes in the mortgage industry affect business?A If this transitions away from government sponsorship of most mortgages, there’s no question rates will go up, underwriting will become stricter and down payment requirements will get larger. In the long term, that has an effect on affordability.We’re doing a little better because our buyers, on average, put 30 percent down and are very well qualified for mortgages.Q  What are your long-term goals for Toll Brothers?A To enhance the brand, and get bigger. There’s a chance we could announce a deal in China this year.We’re looking to take the City Living brand to Washington and Boston. And in New York, 5 to 10 years from now, we better have half a dozen buildings going up in Manhattan and Brooklyn.
Continue reading the main story






